          "body": "Isaiah 45 opens with the most theologically provocative title in the Old Testament: YHWH calls Cyrus His 'anointed' (*mashiach*, 45:1). The word is used elsewhere only of Israel's kings — Saul, David, Solomon — and by implication of the coming Davidic redeemer. Applied here to a Gentile who 'has not known Me' (45:4, 5), the title functions as a theological shock. YHWH is not constrained by Israel's ethnic or cultic boundaries when He selects His instruments of redemption. The specific details of the oracle — shattering bronze gates, releasing exiles without payment (45:13) — correspond precisely to Cyrus's documented decree of 538 BC (Ezra 1:1-4) and to the fall of Babylon reported in the Cyrus Cylinder. The double stated purpose seals the oracle's meaning: Cyrus is to know that YHWH, the God of Israel, called him by name (45:3), and the nations are to know from east to west that there is no one besides YHWH (45:6). The particular act — one king, one city, one campaign — serves a universal epistemological end. This is YHWH's signature move in Isaiah 40-55: the specific historical event is simultaneously the vehicle for the broadest possible theological disclosure."
